> Do you have a specific list of changes in mind?

Two things in particular: 

## 1. More efficient collection handling in Events

Collections that are passed into Events' constructors are cloned and made unmodifiable in the constructor. This is wasteful, as we emit a lot of events, and it's quite possible nobody ever needs the collection. I'd like to change it so the reference to the original collection is stored in the event and a second reference is lazily initialized with the unmodifiable clone once the collection's getter is called. Alternatively, we could replace the reference to the original with the unmodifiable clone on first call to the getter. 

Example:

Current:
```
public abstract class AbstractConstraintEvaluationOnPathNodesEvent extends AbstractConstraintEvaluationForPathEvent
                implements
                ConstraintEvaluationOnPathNodesEvent {
    private final Set<Node> valueNodes;

    public AbstractConstraintEvaluationOnPathNodesEvent(ValidationContext vCxt, Shape shape, Node focusNode,
                    Constraint constraint, Path path, Set<Node> valueNodes) {
        super(vCxt, shape, focusNode, constraint, path);
        this.valueNodes = Collections.unmodifiableSet(new HashSet<>(valueNodes));
    }

    @Override public Set<Node> getValueNodes() {
        return valueNodes;
    }
}
```
Planned:
```
public abstract class AbstractConstraintEvaluationOnPathNodesEvent extends AbstractConstraintEvaluationForPathEvent
                implements
                ConstraintEvaluationOnPathNodesEvent {
    private final Set<Node> valueNodes;
    private Set<Node> valueNodesClone = null;

    public AbstractConstraintEvaluationOnPathNodesEvent(ValidationContext vCxt, Shape shape, Node focusNode,
                    Constraint constraint, Path path, Set<Node> valueNodes) {
        super(vCxt, shape, focusNode, constraint, path);
        this.valueNodes = valueNodes;
    }

    @Override public Set<Node> getValueNodes() {
        if (valueNodes == null) {
             // I think we don't need to synchronize here, not much harm will be done if called multiple times in parallel
             this.valueNodesClone = Collections.unmodifiableSet(new HashSet<>(this.valueNodes));
        }
        return valueNodesClone;
    }
}
```
## 2. Refactor the ValidationListener interface

I am not sure I like the ValidationListener, which has these methods:

```
public interface ValidationListener {

    void onConstraintViolatedEvent(ConstraintEvaluatedEvent e);

    void onConstraintSatisfiedEvent(ConstraintEvaluatedEvent e);

    void onValidationLifecycleEvent(ValidationLifecycleEvent e);

}
``` 

I don't like it much because it requires the following code in the ValidationContext:
```
            if (event instanceof ConstraintEvaluatedEvent){
                if (((ConstraintEvaluatedEvent)event).isValid()){
                    validationListener.onConstraintViolatedEvent((ConstraintEvaluatedEvent) event);
                } else {
                    validationListener.onConstraintSatisfiedEvent((ConstraintEvaluatedEvent) event);
                }
            } else if (event instanceof ValidationLifecycleEvent) {
                validationListener.onValidationLifecycleEvent((ValidationLifecycleEvent) event);
            } else {
                throw new IllegalArgumentException("Cannot handle event " + event);
            }
```
I.e., the interface is prejudiced about what will constitute a separation of events that is relevant to the client. (constraintViolated, constraintSatisfied, or lifecycle). I am not certain what would be better, but I am leaning toward just one method, `onValidationEvent`, and providing a utility class or a base class for listeners that make it easy to select the events one is interested in.

