In my case, its a mix of both legacy RDFConnection implementations from when the link layer did not exist - as well as custom decorations. For example, I was experimenting with a [getMetadata()](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/sql/Connection.html#getMetaData()) method (analoguous to JDBC's connection) in order to allow for obtaining information about what the connection is connected to. For this I used RDFConnectionWrapper as in the provided test case.


On top of that, once I get an RDFConnection from a 'data source' I sometimes wrap the connection with query transformations (sometimes paired with result set post processing).
This way the data source, query transformations and application logic don't have to know each other - at the cost of resulting in a bit of ugly wrapping but that's typically not really an issue - unless when the wrappers don't delegate properly.

```java
    public static RDFConnection wrapWithLinkDecorator(RDFConnection conn, Function<? super RDFLink, ? extends RDFLink> linkDecorator) {
        RDFLink oldLink = RDFLinkAdapter.adapt(conn);
        RDFLink newLink = linkDecorator.apply(oldLink);
        RDFConnection result = RDFConnectionAdapter.adapt(newLink);
        return result;
    }
```

Yes, ideally RDFConnection would just be a presenter for an RDFLink but the link/conn machinery making that assumption and therefore only providing an incomplete wrapping was again an experience like catching a splinter. I am also already looking into whether in my case I can refactor the code to only use the link machinery, but that's quite heavy effort compared to 'completing' the adapters.

I also streamlined null handling in the wrappers
Existing code would use both variants:
```java
// class RDFLinkAdapter
    @Override
    public Graph get() {
        Model m = conn.fetch();
        if ( m == null ) return null;
        return m.getGraph();
    }
```
as well as
```java
// class RDFLinkAdapter
    @Override
    public DatasetGraph getDataset() {
        return conn.fetchDataset().asDatasetGraph(); // fails if fetchDataset returned null
    }
```

I now changed that to:
```java
// class RDFLinkAdapter
    @Override
    public DatasetGraph getDataset() {
        Dataset ds = conn.fetchDataset();
        return ds == null ? null : ds.asDatasetGraph();
    }
```

To motivate this change: There is a bit of unclarity in getDataset()
- It can delegate to fetchDataset() which downloads the dataset
- It can return a dataset **view** over the remote endpoint (where the find method is implemented as sending SPARQL select queries)
- It can return a local (in-memory) dataset
- It may be an unsupported operation and thus yield null or raise UOE

So far I used getDataset() mainly to expose a local in memory datasets where polymorphic views via `Resource.as(class)` are most meaningful.
Conversely, such views are not really meaningful over remote views (each method call results in a remote request) or if getDataset delegates to fetchDataset which then attempts to download all of DBpedia.

Depending on the use case it thus makes sense for getDataset to return null, raise a UOP, return the local copy or a view over remote requests. The contract does not state whether null or UOP should be used - The existing code in the first example above with `RDFLinkAdapter.get()` suggest null is valid!
In any case, I don't think that the adapters are the place to judge which is the 'correct' usage so that's why I added null delegation.
